18. nitere porro, ‘push on’. Horace humorously supposes that people will come crowding round his messenger, eager to know what he has brought. Bentley (without remark, and Orelli supposes, by accident) printed nitere. porro, and this read- ing has been adopted by some editors; but nitere seems to require an adverb much more than vade, and the rhythm is certainly against the pause aster the fifth foot.
